          "id": 20,
          "options": {
            "code": {
              "language": "plaintext",
              "showLineNumbers": false,
              "showMiniMap": false
            },
            "content": "## How to read the GPU metrics\n\nThree complementary signals — each answers a different question. Watch them together.\n\n| Metric | What it answers | Healthy range |\n|---|---|---|\n| **GPU Busy %** (`DCGM_FI_DEV_GPU_UTIL`) | Is any kernel running? (liveness / idle) | 95–100% during training |\n| **Compute Density / SM Active %** (`DCGM_FI_PROF_SM_ACTIVE`) | What % of SMs were scheduled with work? | 40–70% for real mixed ML workloads |\n| **SM Occupancy %** (`DCGM_FI_PROF_SM_OCCUPANCY`) | Of the SMs that ran, how full were they? | 20–40% typical |\n| **Tensor Core Activity %** (`DCGM_FI_PROF_PIPE_TENSOR_ACTIVE`) | % of time tensor pipes ran (bf16/fp16 math) | 15–50% in LLM training |\n\n**Key point for readers:** SM Active below 100% is normal — the workload mixes memory-bound (softmax, reductions, comm) and compute-bound (GEMM) kernels. Treat low SM Active as **room to optimize**, not a fault. Conversely, GPU Busy at 100% alone is not proof of efficient compute — Trainy's post showed you can hit 100% GPU Busy with 0 FLOPs just by reading memory.\n\n## Auto-Switch: Time Series ↔ Stat Grid\n\nPer-node Compute Density and GPU Temperature panels auto-switch based on cluster size:\n- **≤128 nodes** → time series (one line per node)\n- **>128 nodes** → stat grid (one colored tile per node, hover shows Hostname + value)\n\nDriven by hidden variable `$instance_count`. Fallback default is `9999` → stat grid shown.",
            "mode": "markdown"
          },
          "pluginVersion": "11.5.1",
          "title": "",
          "type": "text"
        }
      ],
      "title": "Guide",
      "type": "row"
    },
